\begin_layout Problem
In class, we worked out many properties of a degenerate Fermi gas in three
 dimensions.
 In this problem, you will repeat the process in two dimensions.
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
This may appear to be a purely academic exercise ‚Äì after all, we live in
 a three- dimensional world ‚Äì but it‚Äôs actually experimentally realizable.
 In the analysis we did in class, we assumed the particles were confined
 in a cubical box with equal sides 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

.
 But suppose one of the sides, say in the 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

 direction, is much smaller, so instead of in a cube, the particles are
 in a thin sheet.
 Then the energy spacings between orbitals associated with motion in the
 small dimension will be much larger, and if the spacing between the two
 lowest energy levels is much greater than 
\begin_inset Formula $k_{B}T$
\end_inset

, only the ground state will be occupied.
 In that case the electron gas is effectively two-dimensional in its properties
 and behavior, even though the film has nonzero thickness in the third dimension.
 Suppose we deposit a metal film (on an insulating substrate) that is 10
 atomic layers thick.
 Estimate how low the temperature would have to be in order for the electron
 gas to behave as a two-dimensional system.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
For such a two-dimensional Fermi gas, derive appropriate expressions for
 the Fermi energy and density of states.
 Also determine how the heat capacity varies with temperature (you don‚Äôt
 have to work out an exact expression, but figure out the 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

-dependence).
 Discuss any similarities or differences from the three- dimensional case.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Solution*
1.
 We know that the eigen-energies for the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

particle in a box
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 problem are given by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
E=\frac{n\pi^{2}\hbar^{2}}{2mL^{2}},
\]

\end_inset

On the other hand, because the film is much thinner in the one of the spatial
 dimensions, we have that the size of the box becomes 
\begin_inset Formula $ùëë$
\end_inset

 d in that direction.
 It follows that, the energy spacing 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta E$
\end_inset

 between the first two energy levels (ground state and first excited state)
 in the dimension is approximately given by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\Delta E=\frac{\pi^{2}\hbar^{2}}{2md^{2}},
\]

\end_inset

and even more, if 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta E$
\end_inset

 is much greater than 
\begin_inset Formula $k_{B}T$
\end_inset

, then, only the ground state will be occupied, and the system effectively
 behaves as two-dimensional, which imposes the following condition
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\Delta E\gg k_{B}T,
\]

\end_inset

therefore, it follows that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{\pi^{2}\hbar^{2}}{2md^{2}}\gg k_{B}T,
\]

\end_inset

and in this form, we have the following condition for the temperature 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
T\ll\frac{\pi^{2}\hbar^{2}}{2mk_{B}d^{2}}.
\]

\end_inset

2) For this part we first need to compute the density of states and having
 that we can derive the partition function, and from this all the other
 thermodynamical quantities.
 So, let's begin: we know that the density of states is defined as follows
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
g\left(k\right)dk=\frac{\text{volume in }k\text{ -space of a complete speherical shell}}{\text{volume in }k\text{ -space occupied per allowed state}},
\]

\end_inset

but that was for the 3D case, and in 2D, we have to make some changes, in
 particular, we have the following definition
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
g\left(k\right)dk=\frac{\text{area in }k\text{ -space of a complete speherical shell}}{\text{area in }k\text{ -space occupied per allowed state}},
\]

\end_inset

thus, we have 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
g\left(k\right)dk=\frac{2\pi kdk}{\left(\frac{2\pi}{L}\right)^{2}}\times2,
\]

\end_inset

the factor in the denominator comes from the solution of the solution of
 the Schr√∂dinger equation for a particle in a box, and the overall two comes
 from the spin degeneracy of the electrons.
 And from this we can obtain the following expression 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
g\left(k\right)dk=\frac{L^{2}}{\pi}kdk,
\]

\end_inset

and now, with this in mind let's write the density of states in terms of
 the energy, and in order to to that, we're going to consider that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
E=\frac{\hbar^{2}k^{2}}{m},
\]

\end_inset

and from this it follows that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
dE=\frac{\hbar^{2}}{m}kdk\implies kdk=\frac{m}{\hbar^{2}}dE,
\]

\end_inset

thus, we can rewrite the density of states as 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
g\left(k\right)dk\rightarrow g\left(E\right)dE=\frac{mL^{2}}{\pi\hbar^{2}}dE,
\]

\end_inset

and even more, let's call 
\begin_inset Formula $L^{2}=A$
\end_inset

, then, we have that the density of states can be written as 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
g\left(E\right)dE=\frac{mA}{\pi\hbar^{2}}dE.
\]

\end_inset

Now, for the determination of the Fermi Energy, let's compute 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
N=\int_{0}^{\infty}\frac{g\left(E\right)dE}{\exp\left[\beta\left(E-\mu\right)\right]+1},
\]

\end_inset

at 
\begin_inset Formula $T=0$
\end_inset

, but in this regime, the fermi statistics takes the form of a step function,
 and thus, the previous equation transforms into 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
N=\int_{0}^{E_{F}}g\left(E\right)dE,
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\implies N=\frac{mA}{\pi\hbar^{2}}\int_{0}^{E_{F}}dE,
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\implies\frac{N}{A}=\frac{m}{\pi\hbar^{2}}E_{F},
\]

\end_inset

and making 
\begin_inset Formula $n=N/A$
\end_inset

, we have 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
n=\frac{m}{\pi\hbar^{2}}E_{F},
\]

\end_inset

which implies that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
E_{F}=\frac{\pi\hbar^{2}}{m}n,
\]

\end_inset

and now, if 
\begin_inset Formula $T\neq0$
\end_inset

, then we have to deal with the whole integral, which usually can be recasted
 in terms of the polylogarithm functions, or we can use the Sommerfeld approxima
tion, and in any case, in order to compute the heat capacity, we first need
 to compute the internal energy, and then derive with respect to the temperature
, but first let's focus on the internal energy, which can be computed via
 the expectation value
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
U=\left\langle E\right\rangle ,
\]

\end_inset

which in this kind of statistics is given by
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
U=\int_{0}^{\infty}\frac{Eg\left(E\right)dE}{\exp\left[\beta\left(E-\mu\right)\right]+1},
\]

\end_inset

and now, if we put the density of states previously computed we have that
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
U=\frac{mA}{\pi\hbar^{2}}\int_{0}^{\infty}\frac{EdE}{\exp\left[\beta\left(E-\mu\right)\right]+1},
\]

\end_inset

now, I decided to go with Sommerfeld's approximation, which reads 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
U=\int_{0}^{\mu}Eg\left(E\right)dE+\frac{\pi^{2}}{6}\left(k_{B}T\right)^{2}\left[\frac{d}{dE}\left(Eg\left(E\right)\right)\right]_{\mu}+\cdots,
\]

\end_inset

and from this we have that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\int_{0}^{\mu}Eg\left(E\right)dE=\frac{mA}{\pi\hbar^{2}}\int_{0}^{\mu}EdE,
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\implies\int_{0}^{\mu}Eg\left(E\right)dE=\frac{mA}{2\pi\hbar^{2}}\mu^{2},
\]

\end_inset

and 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{d}{dE}\left(Eg\left(E\right)\right)=\frac{d}{dE}\left(E\frac{mA}{\pi\hbar^{2}}\right),
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\implies\frac{d}{dE}\left(Eg\left(E\right)\right)=\frac{mA}{\pi\hbar^{2}},
\]

\end_inset

therefore, we have that the internal energy is given by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
U\approx\frac{mA}{2\pi\hbar^{2}}\mu^{2}+\frac{\pi^{2}}{6}\frac{mA}{\pi\hbar^{2}}\left(k_{B}T\right)^{2},
\]

\end_inset

and from this it follows that the heat capacity, which is defined by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
C=\frac{\partial U}{\partial T},
\]

\end_inset

is given by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
C=\frac{\pi^{2}}{3}\frac{mA}{\pi\hbar^{2}}k_{B}^{2}T,
\]

\end_inset

which means that the heat capacity depends linearly with the temperature,
 which is the same result as the three dimensional case, up to some constants,
 of course, which come from the differences between the density of states.
 Now, let me elaborate a little more on this:in both cases, 2D and 3D, the
 heat capacity shows a linear dependence on temperature (T) at low temperatures
 which is where the Sommerfeld approximation is good, on the other hand
 the key difference lies in the density of states, as stated before, in
 the 2D, the density of states scales linearly with the wave vector 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

, whereas in 3D, it scales as 
\begin_inset Formula $k^{2}$
\end_inset

, and this leads to a different pre-factor in the final expression for the
 heat capacity.
 And finally, while both show a temperature dependence, the pre-factor in
 the 2D case is smaller than in 3D, which indicates that a 2D electron gas
 will have a lower heat capacity compared to a 3D gas with the same number
 of electrons and temperature.
\begin_inset Newpage newpage
\end_inset


\end_layout

